ng of West Java, 1948 -- t13. Fighting over Depok. From colonial privilege to Indonesian citizenship, 1942-1949 -- t14. A successful transition. The Chinese in revolutionary Aceh, 1945-1949 -- t15. Navigating contested middle ground. Ethnic Chinese in revolutionary East Sumatra, 1945-1950 -- t16. Everyday life of the Chinese in revolutionary Padang, 1945-1948 -- t17. Playing it safe. Survival strategies of the Indian community in East Sumatran cities, 1945-1946 -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the authors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aRevolutionary Worlds looks at the Indonesian revolution (1945-1949) from a local and regional perspective. In several contributions, Indonesian and Dutch researchers bring to life the revolutionary world from widely differing perspectives. The authors explain how Indonesian, Chinese, Indian and Eurasian civilians, fighters, farmers and officials experienced and shaped the chaotic period between 1945 and 1950. The book focuses on survival strategies, mobilization, and the use of force against the backdrop of the Indonesian and Dutch authorities' efforts to gain or maintain control. Uniting two national historiographical traditions which have long remained largely separate, Revolutionary Worlds is the result of a special collaboration between the Indonesian research project Proklamasi, Kemerdekaan, Revolusi dan Perang di Indonesia ('Proclamation, Independence, Revolution and War in Indonesia', Universitas Gadjah Mada, Yogyakarta) and the Dutch research group of the Regional Studies project, under the umbrella of the research programme Independence, Decolonization, Violence and War in Indonesia, 1945-1950.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 4aAUP Algemeen. 4aColonial Studies. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary History. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  aIndonesia, independence war, military history, revolution.1 aAhmad, Taufik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmbar Sasi, Galuh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBent, Maarten van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEickhoff, Martijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEickhoff, Martijn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErniwati,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFakih, Farabi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrakking, Roel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrakking, Roel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarahap, Apriani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoek, Anne-Lot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoogenboom, Ireen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHusain, Sarkawi B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Julianto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrsyam, Tri Wahyuning M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinken, Gerry van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinken, Gerry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPurwanto, Bambang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUmar, Mawa